In this posting:
[1] Algeria
[2] Israel

******
[1] Algeria
Date: Wed 28 Apr 2021
Source: Annasr Online [in Arabic, trans. Mod.SF, abridged, edited]
https://cutt.ly/TbgTrAw


The directorate of agricultural services in the state of Constantine registered a new outbreak of brucellosis among cattle in the Djebel El Ouahch district. The number of people infected with this disease in Bouziane Hamma increased to 7, and the directorate decided to impose strict penalties and implement legal procedures for every seller of milk and milk products who did not comply with the protocol.

The veterinary inspector, Dr. Bin Amer Murad, confirmed that the analyzes conducted at the level of cows in the Djebel El Ouahch district showed that 8 heads had been infected with brucellosis. The doctor also issued an appeal to citizens urging them to stop consuming unpasteurized milk and other dairy products, which comes directly from an unreliable source, because it endangers their lives.

The veterinary doctor at the Municipal Office of the Directorate of Agricultural services in Hamma Bouziane, Ramadhani Layla, confirmed that the disease was discovered after receiving a letter from the Infectious Diseases Department of Hamma Bouziane Hospital about the infection of 3 people with brucellosis. The spokeswoman added that 2 shops caused the infection of patients, one of which was located in the neighborhood of Shu'bat al-Madhobh and the 2nd in the center of the city of Hamma Bouziane. The analyzes confirmed the presence of the bacteria causing the disease, and the 2 shops were closed.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>
via
ProMED-MENA
<promed-mena@promedmail.org>

[As in other North African countries, brucellosis is endemic and enzootic in Algeria. The consumption of raw milk and milk products that have not undergone pasteurization is the most common route of human infection in these countries. Similar events were reported by ProMED in 2021 in other Algerian provinces (Jijel, M'Sila, Batna, and Bouira).

Brucellosis is one of the world's major zoonoses. A bacterial infection that spreads from animals to people, it is common to many mammal species (sheep, goats, cattle, pigs, dogs, etc.) and humans. Several species of _Brucella_ have been identified with various specificities. _Brucella abortus_ affects cattle, _Brucella melitensis_ affects small ruminants, and _Brucella suis_ affects pigs. _Brucella melitensis_ is the most prevalent species causing human brucellosis. - Mod.SF]

[It will be helpful to obtain information on the species (_B. abortus_ or _B. melitensis_) involved in the Algerian outbreaks; see also item 2. - Mod.AS

