******
[2] Israel
Date: Sat 1 May 2021
Source: Hachaklait Clinical Veterinary Services, head veterinarian's weekly report no. 18/2021 [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS, abridged, edited; subscription required]
http://www.hachaklait.org.il


Tests for brucellosis, applied in the large dairy cattle herd in Revivim, have detected one more positive cow, additional to the one reported last week. Another 3 cows were found suspects. The findings underline the importance of continuous, intensive surveillance in herds situated in close proximity to sheep and goat flocks that are not subject to periodic veterinary inspections.

Recently, a disposal site with carcasses of small ruminants was found 300 m [984 ft] from the Revivim dairy cattle operation. The carcasses were suspected to come from flocks in the Bedouin settlement Bir Hadaj, less than 3 km [1.9 mi] from Revivim (map at https://tinyurl.com/kz9aj84w).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[For the locations of Revivim and Bir Hadaj, see map at https://tinyurl.com/kz9aj84w. The distance between them is less than 3 km [1.9 mi].

The Revivim dairy cattle operation in southern Israel is one of the country's 10 leading milk-producing enterprises, counting more than 2000 animals, including about 1300 lactating cows. In October 2015, this herd was found infected by _B. melitensis_. The discovery was preceded by the identification of human infection among its personnel (see 20151031.3757610 and subsequent postings; in total, 5 human cases were diagnosed). Control measures, including movement restrictions, were undertaken, and a "test and slaughter" policy was applied. A secondary infection was discovered in another dairy farm that had purchased calves from Revivim earlier.

During the initial eradication activities, until 2016, more than 200 positive cows were culled. Sporadic new cases have been identified during the subsequent years in spite of the biosecurity measures applied, testing periodically performed, and calf vaccination policy re-instated.

At present, 7 out of Israel's (about) 700 dairy farms are known to be infected with _B. melitensis_, of which 5 are in the southern region, where grazing small ruminants are abundant. The leakage of _B. melitensis_ into dairy cattle operations reflects the worsening of the brucellosis situation among Israel's sheep/goats, as described in detail in posting 20150801.3550984. This should not surprise; in various Mediterranean countries (for example, Spain, Portugal, Italy, Greece, Egypt, Turkey, Algeria), _B. melitensis_ has been regularly isolated from cattle that were in direct or indirect contact with infected sheep and/or goats.

The continuous circulation of _B.melitensis_ in Israel's extensively-held sheep and goat flocks has been attributed to insufficient control measures and vaccination coverage (by the 'Rev 1' vaccine). This circulation has led to increased number of human cases ("Malta fever").

During the 1st 16 weeks of 2021 (as of 24 Apr 2021), 31 human cases have been reported by the Ministry of Health, compared to 27 during the same period in 2020. The total number of human cases officially reported during 2020 was 272. It is estimated that the factual number of infections is at least 10-fold of the officially reported, hospitalised cases.

The issue has become subject to deliberations in the Knesset (Israel's parliament) and to a criticizing report by the State Comptroller in the 2018 annual issue (https://tinyurl.com/r48shtpe; click page 831 for PDF or Word documents; in Hebrew). The State Veterinary Services are obliged to cope with budget deficiencies and the privatisation of State agencies, which, in particular, affected activities in backyard and extensively held flocks. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED map:
HaDarom, Israel: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8340099,29822]
